fields.title: Slam Dunk 1
fields.author: INOUE TAKEHIKO
fields.summary: Slam Dunk is a Japanese sports manga series written and illustrated by Takehiko Inoue. It was first serialized in Shueisha's shōnen manga magazine Weekly Shōnen Jump from 1990 to 1996. The 31 collected tankōbon volumes of the manga have sold over 120 million copies in Japan and 150 million copies worldwide, making it one of the best-selling manga series of all time.

fields.title: One Piece 1
fields.author: Eiichiro Oda
fields.summary: One Piece is a Japanese shōnen manga series written and illustrated by Eiichiro Oda. It has been serialized in Shueisha's shōnen manga magazine Weekly Shōnen Jump since July 1997, and has been collected into 102 tankōbon volumes. The story follows the adventures of Monkey D. Luffy, a young man who gains the power to stretch his body like rubber after eating a Devil Fruit. Luffy sets out to find the One Piece, a treasure left by the former King of the Pirates, Gol D. Roger.

fields.title: Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone
fields.author: J.K. Rowling
fields.summary: Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone is a fantasy novel by J. K. Rowling. The first novel in the Harry Potter series, it follows Harry Potter, an orphan who learns on his eleventh birthday that he is a wizard, famous in the wizarding world for surviving an attack by the evil Lord Voldemort when he was only a baby. Harry is summoned from his life as an unwanted child by his parents' friend Albus Dumbledore, a powerful sorcerer and headmaster of Hogwarts School of Witchcraft and Wizardry. Harry is sorted into Gryffindor House and begins his education in magic. During the school year, Harry and his friends Ron Weasley and Hermione Granger investigate the Sorcerer's Stone, an object that can grant immortality. They are opposed by Voldemort, who is trying to steal the Stone to regain his full body. In the end, Harry defeats Voldemort, saving the Stone and himself.

fields.title: The Lord of the Rings
fields.author: J.R.R. Tolkien
fields.summary: The Lord of the Rings is an epic high fantasy trilogy written by English philologist and University of Oxford professor J. R. R. Tolkien. The story began as a sequel to Tolkien's 1937 fantasy novel The Hobbit, but eventually developed into a much larger work. Written in stages between 1937 and 1949, with much of it being written during World War II, it was originally published in three volumes in 1954 and 1955. It has since been reprinted numerous times and translated into at least 38 languages, becoming one of the best-selling novels ever written.

fields.title: The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy
fields.author: Douglas Adams
fields.summary: The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy is a comedic science fiction series created by Douglas Adams. The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy is a pan-galactic encyclopaedia and travel guide for hitchhikers, owned by Arthur Dent, a hapless Englishman, following the destruction of the Earth by the Vogons, a race of unpleasant and bureaucratic aliens. Arthur escapes Earth's destruction with his friend Ford Prefect, who turns out to be an alien researcher who had been stranded on Earth for fifteen years while gathering information for the titular Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy.

fields.title: The Da Vinci Code
fields.author: Dan Brown
fields.summary: The Da Vinci Code is a 2003 mystery thriller novel by Dan Brown. The story follows Robert Langdon, a professor of symbology at Harvard University, and Sophie Neveu, a police cryptologist, in their investigation of the murder of Jacques Saunière, the curator of the Louvre Museum in Paris. The murder scene is filled with cryptic clues that lead Langdon and Neveu on a chase around the city, as they try to solve the mystery behind the Priory of Sion, a secret society that has been protecting a centuries-old secret.

fields.title: To Kill a Mockingbird
fields.author: Harper Lee
fields.summary: To Kill a Mockingbird is a novel by Harper Lee published in 1960. It won the Pulitzer Prize and was adapted into an Academy Award-winning film in 1962. The novel is set in the fictional town of Maycomb, Alabama, during the Great Depression. It tells the story of Jean Louise 'Scout' Finch and her brother, Jeremy Atticus 'Jem' Finch, as they come of age under the guidance of their father, Atticus, who is a lawyer. Atticus is appointed to defend Tom Robinson, a black man who has been falsely accused of raping a white woman. The trial is a watershed moment for Scout and Jem, as they learn about the prejudice and injustice that exists in the world.

fields.title: The Catcher in the Rye
fields.author: J. D. Salinger
fields.summary: The Catcher in the Rye is a novel by J. D. Salinger, first published in 1951. The story follows Holden Caulfield, a teenage boy who is expelled from Pencey Prep, an elite boarding school in Pennsylvania. Holden then travels to New York City for a few days before returning home. During his time in New York, Holden reflects on his life and the world around him. The novel is known for its exploration of themes such as alienation, adolescence, and the loss of innocence.

fields.title: Pride and Prejudice
fields.author: Jane Austen
fields.summary: Pride and Prejudice is a novel of manners written by Jane Austen. It was first published in 1813. The story follows Elizabeth Bennet, the second of five sisters, as she deals with issues of manners, upbringing, morality, education, and marriage in the society of the landed gentry of early 19th-century England. Elizabeth is a strong-willed and intelligent woman who is determined to marry for love rather than money. She is initially prejudiced against Fitzwilliam Darcy, a wealthy and eligible bachelor, but she eventually comes to realize that he is a kind and generous man.
